.\" Man page for blockman.sh
.TH blockman 1 "July 02, 2025" "Version 1.0.0" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
blockman \- manage named shell script blocks in config files
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B blockman
[\fB--file\fR \fIFILE\fR | \fB-s\fR \fIFILE\fR]
[\fB--body\fR \fISTR\fR | \fB-b\fR \fISTR\fR | \fB--contentFile\fR \fIFILE\fR]
[\fB--append\fR | \fB-a\fR]
[\fB--transform\fR \fICOMMAND\fR]
[\fB--show\fR | \fB--list\fR]
[\fB--extract\fR]
[\fB--check\fR]
[\fB--dry-run\fR]
[\fB--format\fR \fIFORMAT\fR]
[\fB--comment-prefix\fR \fIPREFIX\fR]
[\fB--version\fR]
[\fB--help\fR]
[\fIBLOCK_ID\fR]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B blockman
is a shell script for managing named blocks of text, typically shell script snippets, within configuration files. It supports operations like inserting, removing, appending to, transforming, and extracting these named blocks.

Each block is identified by a unique ID and is delimited by comments, e.g., "# BEGIN my_block_id" and "# END my_block_id". The comment prefix itself is configurable.

All actions performed by \fBblockman\fR are logged to a file within \fB/var/log/blockman/\fR (or a configurable path), and a diff is output to stdout by default for modifications. Log format can be either plain text or JSON.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
\fB--file\fR \fIFILE\fR, \fB--in\fR \fIFILE\fR, \fB--inFile\fR \fIFILE\fR, \fB-s\fR \fIFILE\fR
Specify the configuration file to operate on. This is a required option for most operations.
.TP
\fB--body\fR \fISTR\fR, \fB--content\fR \fISTR\fR, \fB--block\fR \fISTR\fR, \fB-b\fR \fISTR\fR, \fB-c\fR \fISTR\fR
Provide the content (body) for a block directly as a string. If the block does not exist, it will be created. If it exists, its content will be replaced unless \fB--append\fR is used.
.TP
\fB--contentFile\fR \fIFILE\fR, \fB--blockFile\fR \fIFILE\fR, \fB--bodyFile\fR \fIFILE\fR
Provide the content (body) for a block from the specified file. Similar behavior to \fB--body\fR regarding creation or replacement.
.TP
\fB--append\fR, \fB-a\fR
Used in conjunction with \fB--body\fR or \fB--contentFile\fR. If the block already exists, the new content will be appended to its existing content instead of replacing it.
.TP
\fB--transform\fR \fICOMMAND\fR
Apply a shell command or pipeline to the content of an existing block. The block's content is piped to \fICOMMAND\fR, and the output of \fICOMMAND\fR replaces the block's content.
.TP
\fB--show\fR, \fB--list\fR
Display the content of the specified block ID to stdout. No modifications are made.
.TP
\fB--extract\fR
Display the content of the specified block ID to stdout, and then remove the block (including its start/end markers) from the file.
.TP
\fB--check\fR
Check the integrity of blocks within the file (e.g., unclosed blocks).
.TP
\fB--dry-run\fR
Perform all operations without making any actual changes to the file system. Output the proposed changes to stdout.
.TP
\fB--format\fR \fIFORMAT\fR
Specify the log output format. Currently supports \fBplain\fR (default) or \fBjson\fR.
.TP
\fB--comment-prefix\fR \fIPREFIX\fR
Specify the character(s) to be used as the comment prefix for block markers (e.g., \fB#\fR or \fB//\fR). This overrides the \fBBLOCKMAN_COMMENT_CHAR\fR setting from configuration files for the current command execution.
.TP
\fB--version\fR
Display the version of \fBblockman\fR.
.TP
\fB--help\fR, \fB-h\fR, \fI-?\fR
Display a help message and exit.
.TP
\fIBLOCK_ID\fR
The unique identifier for the block to operate on. If omitted for \fI*rc\fR or \fI*profile\fR files, it defaults to an uppercase version of the filename (e.g., \fI.bashrc\fR becomes \fIBASHRC_D\fR). Required for other file types.
.SH CONFIGURATION
.B blockman
reads its configuration from two main files, applied in the following order:
.RS
.TP
\fB1. /etc/default/blockman\fR
The system-wide default configuration file. Variables set here define the system-wide policy.
.IP
.B Important:
If \fBENABLE_SYSLOG\fR, \fBBLOCKMAN_LOG_BASE_DIR\fR, or \fBLOG_FORMAT\fR are defined in this file, their values are enforced as system policy and cannot be overridden by user-specific configurations or command-line arguments.
.TP
\fB2. ~/.config/blockman.conf\fR (or path specified by \fBBBLOCKMAN_USER_CONFIG\fR environment variable)
The user-specific configuration file. Settings here override those in \fB/etc/default/blockman\fR, except for the policy-enforced variables mentioned above.
.RE
.PP
The following variables can be configured within these files:
.TP
\fBSTART_KEYWORDS\fR
A pipe-separated list of keywords (e.g., "START|BEGIN") used to identify the beginning of a block marker. Default: "START|BEGIN|HEAD".
.TP
\fBEND_KEYWORDS\fR
A pipe-separated list of keywords (e.g., "END|FINISH") used to identify the end of a block marker. Default: "END|FINISH|TAIL".
.TP
\fBBLOCKMAN_COMMENT_CHAR\fR
The character(s) used as a comment prefix for block markers (e.g., "#" or "//"). Default: "#". This can also be overridden for a single command using the \fB--comment-prefix\fR option.
.TP
\fBBLOCKMAN_LOG_BASE_DIR\fR
The base directory where blockman will store its log files. Default: "/var/log/blockman".
.TP
\fBLOG_FORMAT\fR
The format of the log entries. Supported values are "plain" (default) or "json".
.TP
\fBENABLE_SYSLOG\fR
Set to "1" to enable syslog integration for logging actions, or "0" to disable (default). Requires the `logger` command to be available on the system.
.SH FILES
.TP
\fB/etc/default/blockman\fR
System-wide configuration file. See \fBCONFIGURATION\fR section for details on policy enforcement.
.TP
\fB~/.config/blockman.conf\fR
User-specific configuration file. Can be overridden by the \fBBBLOCKMAN_USER_CONFIG\fR environment variable. See \fBCONFIGURATION\fR section.
.TP
\fB/var/log/blockman/\fR
Default directory for blockman log files. This can be configured via \fBBLOCKMAN_LOG_BASE_DIR\fR.
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
\fB0\fR (\fBSUCCESS\fR)
The command completed successfully.
.TP
\fB1\fR (\fBERR_GENERAL\fR)
A general or unspecified error occurred.
.TP
\fB2\fR (\fBERR_INVALID_ARG\fR)
An invalid or missing command-line argument was provided (e.g., missing \fB--file\fR, unexpected argument).
.TP
\fB3\fR (\fBERR_FILE_NOT_FOUND\fR)
The specified input file does not exist.
.TP
\fB4\fR (\fBERR_PERMISSION_DENIED\fR)
The script lacks necessary read or write permissions for the specified file.
.TP
\fB5\fR (\fBERR_BLOCK_NOT_FOUND\fR)
An operation requiring an existing block (e.g., \fB--transform\fR or \fB--extract\fR) was attempted, but the specified block ID was not found in the file.
.TP
\fB7\fR (\fBERR_BLOCK_INTEGRITY\fR)
The block integrity check (\fB--check\fR) found issues such as unclosed blocks, nested or duplicate start markers, or unmatched end markers.
.TP
\fB8\fR (\fBERR_TRANSFORM_FAILED\fR)
The command or pipeline provided to \fB--transform\fR failed (returned a non-zero exit code).
.TP
\fB9\fR (\fBERR_LOGGING\fR)
The script encountered an issue related to logging (e.g., unable to create the log directory).
